turn.2: King's Lynn  King's Lynn, known until 1537 as Bishop's Lynn, is an English seaport and market town in Norfolk, about north of London, north-east of Peterborough, north north-east of Cambridge and west of Norwich.
turn.6: The etymology of King's Lynn is uncertain.
turn.7: Are there any other interesting aspects about this article?
turn.8: The name "Lynn" is said to be derived from the body of water near the town: the Welsh word "llyn", means a lake; but the name is plausibly of Anglo-Saxon origin, from the word "lean", implying a tenure in fee or farm.
turn.10: As the Domesday Book mentions many saltings at Lena (Lynn), an area of partitioned pools or small lakes may have existed there at that time (1085).
turn.11: What did they do with the saltings?
turn.12: The salt may even have contributed to Herbert de Losinga's interest in the modest parish.
